      "note_no": "568",
      "note": "Cf. 2:65 and n. 79."
    }
  ],
  "en_notes_asad": [
    {
      "note_no": "62",
      "note": "Lit., \"lest We obliterate the faces\" - i.e., that towards which one turns, or that which one faces, with expectation ('Abduh in Manar V, 144 ff.) - \"and bring them back to their ends\". It is to be noted that the term dubur (of which adbar is the plural) does not always signify the \"back\" of a thing - as most of the translators assume - but often stands for its \"last part\" or \"end\" (cf. Lane III, 846)."
    },
